'''José Escolástico Andrino''' (1817, in [[Guatemala City]] &ndash; July 14, 1862 in [[San Salvador]]) was a [[El Salvador|Salvadoran]] [[composer]], considered to be the founder of the [[classical music]] scene in his country. In 1845, he established a [[College or university school of music|Conservatory]] in San Salvador, where he both composed and taught. He wrote two [[symphony|symphonies]], three [[mass (music)|masses]], a set of [[variation (music)|variation]]s for [[violin]] and [[orchestra]], and one [[opera]] ''La Mora generosa'' (the Generous Blackberry).
==References== *{{cite news |accessdate = 2007-03-17 |url = http://archive.laprensa.com.sv/20011018/revista_dominical/rdo3.asp |title = 150 años de música académica |work = La Prensa Graficá de El Salvador |date = October 18, 2001 |language = Spanish |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070401153328/http://archive.laprensa.com.sv/20011018/revista_dominical/rdo3.asp |archivedate = April 1, 2007 |df = }}
