{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2016}} {{Infobox writer | name = Zander Sherman | image = ZanderSherman.jpg | imagesize = | caption = Sherman at the 2012 Book Lovers' Ball | pseudonym = | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Muskoka, Ontario]] | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Nonfiction writer | nationality = Canadian | period = | genre = | subject = | notableworks = ''[[The Curiosity of School]]'' | movement = | influences = | influenced = | signature = | website = {{url|www.zandersherman.com}} }}
'''Zander Sherman''' (born 1986) is a Canadian author and journalist.
==Early life and education== Sherman is the great-grandson of Frank A. Sherman, cofounder of [[Dofasco]], a steel company in [[Hamilton, Ontario]]. Sherman grew up in [[Muskoka]], where he was [[homeschooled]] until the age of thirteen. His father, Jamie, is an artist, [[glassblower]], and musician.<ref>[http://www.thespec.com/news-story/6140773-for-dofasco-founding-family-blood-is-thicker-than-water// For Dofasco founding family, blood is thicker than water.] ''The Hamilton Spectator,'' November 28, 2015.</ref>
==Career== Sherman's debut work was published in 2012 by [[Penguin Random House]]. ''The Curiosity of School: Education and the Dark Side of Enlightenment''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/795007313|title=The curiosity of school : education and the dark side of enlightenment|last=Zander.|first=Sherman,|date=2012|publisher=Viking|isbn=9780670066438|location=Toronto|oclc=795007313}}</ref> debuted on the national bestseller list,<ref>[http://archive.constantcontact.com/fs008/1101791314113/archive/1110989163956.html "Adult Trade Newsletter."] Transatlantic Literary Agency, Fall, 2012.</ref> where it generated wide-ranging response from critics.<ref>[https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/books-and-media/book-reviews/zander-sherman-rambles-through-the-history-of-education/article4511747// Zander Sherman rambles through the history of education.] ''The Globe & Mail,'' August 31, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.quillandquire.com/review/the-curiosity-of-school-education-and-the-dark-side-of-enlightenment// "The Curiosity of School: Education and the Dark Side of Enlightenment."] ''Quill & Quire'', September 1, 2012.</ref> Educator Paul W. Bennett described the book as "the most stimulating Canadian contribution to the Great Education Debate in decades."<ref>[http://thechronicleherald.ca/books/132177-lack-of-curiosity-kills-the-education-system// "Lack of curiosity kills the education system."] ''Chronicle Herald'', September 2, 2012.</ref>
Sherman has since contributed to The Globe & Mail,<ref>https://www.theglobeandmail.com/search/?q=zander+Sherman</ref> and written for numerous magazines including Esquire<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a44097/brother-with-schizophrenia/|title=Schizophrenia Stole My Brother. This Is How I Got Him Back.|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> and The Believer.<ref>http://www.believermag.com/issues/201511/?read=article_sherman ''The Believer'', Fall, 2015.</ref> In 2017, he consulted on "Murder in Cottage Country," a co-produced documentary by [[CBC News]] and The Walrus Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thewalrus.ca/missing-in-cottage-country/|title=Cottage Country Murder|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
== Personal life == Sherman composes music under the name Larch.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.muskokaregion.com/whatson-story/6408841-larch-giving-the-gift-of-music-to-the-people-of-muskoka/|title=Larch—giving the gift of music to the people of Muskoka|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref>
